Perhaps a fisheye lens is too much for a birdhouse.
One never learns from experience.
I should have known better, since I already built one with a "normal" lens before.
I will write more about it over the weekend once I have installed the second one.
Let's just say that the birds will have a better internet connection than I did in 2015.
At least that's the plan.
The box, in which there is already a nest, uses up a lot of WLAN data.
With the other one, it's a bit more difficult for him to go online.
Okay, I've hung up the new nest box today. That's how it looks at its new spot in the garden.
But let's go back a bit. No one asks: "What exactly is inside?"
At the top is one of these ESP32 camera boards with a camera featuring a fisheye lens and an IR-LED, which I took from a Raspberry Pi camera.
The strange shape of this plastic box is due to the swivel side wall of the nest box. I bought it like that and couldn't change it, so I had to build around it.
Since there is no electricity in the garden, the whole setup is powered by a solar panel and a 2600 mAh 18650 cell.
I didn't photograph the cell or the charger, but here's a picture of the panel.
In the gray box, which hangs on the side of the nest box, is the battery.
When it is charged, I have a runtime of about 4 hours.
That's what I call a feature. That way, the birds also get some privacy.
At first, I wasn't sure whether the internet in our garden would be sufficient for this setup. The old access points I replaced last autumn wouldn't have been enough.
But the new ones cover this area very well.
That's almost a pity, because I had planned to install a TP-Link cpe210 on the roof and aim it downward into the garden.
Perhaps I'll do that later, if/when I set up more birdhouses with cameras. Especially in areas that are further away from the house, I probably will need that.
Now the camera is offline, and I don't know why. It turned off just one hour after sunset.
Perhaps the battery did not charge further three hours before sunset because there was not enough light.
Or slightly less than half a day was too little to fully charge the battery.
I'll have to wait and see what happens tomorrow.
I don't have telemetry for the battery. I might have to change that in the future.
In general, I think having a few more sensors would be a good thing.
And perhaps a battery that at least theoretically is capable of keeping the device running overnight.
Oh, and another lens.
Fisheye is quite excessive.
But I'm already looking for parts on Digikey so that I can build my own board specifically for that purpose.
Or maybe not. We'll see.
And it is still offline.
That's great.
According to the actual solar cells on the house, we only have about 90 minutes of proper sunlight.
Let's wait another hour or two to see what happens – or maybe not.
Still offline.
It's never easy either.
It turned out that on the USB-C breakout board I used to connect the charger, the 5 V and GND were swapped on the silkscreen.
I swapped the cables and now the charging indicator is lit.
The ESP didn't come online immediately. Let's wait a few minutes.
An hour has passed and he is still offline.
It looks like he's restarting and triggering a Tasmota reset function.
I think the panel is simply useless. I've now ordered a larger one and hope that will work.
Check out what I found in my workshop.
A 24-V panel. Unfortunately, the sun is already so low (and partly blocked by a tree), that the value practically drops to zero as soon as I turn the device on.
I'll probably have to wait until tomorrow to see if it's sufficient for this setup or if I need the better panel I ordered.
According to Amazon, I bought the panel in 2021, and it is supposed to provide 12 V at a maximum of 1.2 A.
So either something is wrong with the panel or with my multimeter, or the data has changed.
Good news!
You have changed the data, and the ones I have are wrong.
The old one and also the new listing title refer to it as a 12 V 10 W panel.
That is why I never delete old emails.
Oh look! The thing went online again for about half a minute around an hour ago.
Perhaps the panel charged the battery just long enough for 38 seconds of runtime. For that, it only took a little more than two hours.
Guess what: Today it's cloudy. Therefore, I'm not sure whether the (probably broken) solar panel can even generate enough power.
Let's wait and see.
Update: I have installed the new panel and it now seems to be working.
It could still go offline as soon as the sun sets, but let's give it a chance.
Funfact: I'm using the Ping integration in Home Assistant to check whether it's online or not.
The average connection time is 102 ms. Not particularly good, but also not incredibly bad.
